\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{amsmath}
\usepackage{siunitx}

\begin{document}

\title{Physics Problem: Power Expended in Resistances}
\author{University of London}
\date{}
\maketitle

\section*{Problem Statement}

A battery having an electromotive force (emf) of \SI{24}{\volt} and an internal resistance of \SI{2}{\ohm} is connected to two resistances arranged (a) in series and (b) in parallel. If the resistances are \SI{4}{\ohm} and \SI{6}{\ohm}, respectively, calculate the watts expended in each resistance, in each of the two cases.

\section*{Solution}

\subsection*{(a) Series Connection}

In a series connection, the total resistance \( R_{\text{total}} \) is the sum of all resistances:

\[
R_{\text{total}} = R_{\text{internal}} + R_1 + R_2 = 2 + 4 + 6 = \SI{12}{\ohm}
\]

The current \( I \) through the circuit is given by Ohm's law:

\[
I = \frac{V_{\text{emf}}}{R_{\text{total}}} = \frac{24}{12} = \SI{2}{\ampere}
\]

The power expended in each resistance is given by \( P = I^2 R \).

For the \SI{4}{\ohm} resistor:

\[
P_1 = I^2 R_1 = (2)^2 \times 4 = \SI{16}{\watt}
\]

For the \SI{6}{\ohm} resistor:

\[
P_2 = I^2 R_2 = (2)^2 \times 6 = \SI{24}{\watt}
\]

\subsection*{(b) Parallel Connection}

In a parallel connection, the total resistance \( R_{\text{total}} \) is given by:

\[
\frac{1}{R_{\text{total}}} = \frac{1}{R_{\text{internal}}} + \frac{1}{R_1} + \frac{1}{R_2} = \frac{1}{2} + \frac{1}{4} + \frac{1}{6}
\]

Calculating the total resistance:

\[
\frac{1}{R_{\text{total}}} = \frac{6 + 3 + 2}{12} = \frac{11}{12}
\]

Thus,

\[
R_{\text{total}} = \frac{12}{11} \approx \SI{1.09}{\ohm}
\]

The total current \( I \) is:

\[
I = \frac{V_{\text{emf}}}{R_{\text{total}}} = \frac{24}{\frac{12}{11}} = \frac{24 \times 11}{12} = \SI{22}{\ampere}
\]

The voltage across each resistor in parallel is the same as the emf minus the voltage drop across the internal resistance:

\[
V_{\text{across}} = V_{\text{emf}} - I \times R_{\text{internal}} = 24 - 22 \times 2 = \SI{20}{\volt}
\]

The power expended in each resistance is given by \( P = \frac{V^2}{R} \).

For the \SI{4}{\ohm} resistor:

\[
P_1 = \frac{V_{\text{across}}^2}{R_1} = \frac{20^2}{4} = \SI{100}{\watt}
\]

For the \SI{6}{\ohm} resistor:

\[
P_2 = \frac{V_{\text{across}}^2}{R_2} = \frac{20^2}{6} \approx \SI{66.67}{\watt}
\]

\end{document}
```

